===Etymology===
From {{etyl|ga|en}} {{m|ga|bean sí}}, from {{etyl|sga|en}} {{m|sga|ben síd||lit=woman of the fairy mound}}, from {{etyl|sga|en}} {{m|sga|ben||woman}}, from {{etyl|cel-pro|en}} {{m|cel-pro|*benā}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*gʷḗn}} + {{etyl|sga|en}} {{m|sga|síd||fairy mound}}, from {{etyl|cel-pro|en}} {{m|cel-pro|*sedos}}, {{m|cel-pro|*sīdos||mound (inhabited by fairies)}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*sēds}}, {{m|ine-pro|*sed-||seat}}. The term {{m|en||banshee}} entered English in 1771.

